<Pics>None<//Pics>< text>
Well I used to give this restaurant a 5 star review but ever since they got a new cook I had to write a new review. I need to let you know that the Chile Verde tast like it is from the can. I used to go and eat there at least 3 times a week. The wet burrito was awesome and the tacos tasted just as good. I am sorry to say the new cook does not stand a chance. I won't be returning to eat there in till they get the other cook back or find someone that can cook like him. Good luck

This is an update on this restaurant. They got the old cook back. I eat here at least 2 times a week maybe more. I call in my orders most of the time, that way you don't have to wait long. Sometimes they don't answer the phone or they put you on hold and forget about you. But the food is good and it is definitely worth the wait. I would recommend eating her.< /text>

< review>
Food was subpar. I asked for no vegetables and what do you know? They added vegetables. Then when I returned my food because it was not what I ordered, they took it back to pick the veggies off instead of making me a new a new one. They did a poor job of picking the veggies off mind you, AND my torta was cold by the time I got it back. Also I asked for extra salsa in a cup from the young woman working there and she didnt follow through. Had to ask the guy that brought my food out and she didnt even have the courtesy to apologize. She just asked, "did he give you the salsa?" So she knew she screwed up but didnt apologize. So inconsiderate. By the way it doesnt take 15min to make a torta. Dont go there you will wait a lifetime for your food even when youre the only patron in the restaurant.<//review>

< Name>
Kristen Talley< /Name>
<Date>1510793842902<//Date><Rate>5< /Rate><Text>Sharetea is just down the street from USD, so there are always students here, no matter the time of day. Fortunately, no one seems to ever take the barstool seating along the front of the joint, so even when they are packed, there is always a place for a few people to sit. The selection of flavors is limited; they definitely don't have all of the flavors you could find at places like Tea 'N More. That being said, the quality of tea, coffee, and boba is spectacular.  Most tea shops overkill the sweetness of their teas, but Sharetea serves strong tea that you can actually taste underneath the milk, honey, and/or flavor of your choice. My advice is to go to Pho Kitchen across the street for filet mignon pho and then visit Sharetea for dessert and a game of cards or Jenga.</Text>< pictures>

<UserId.>117472077896976204581< /UserId.><name>eB B<//name><Time>1605324558031<//Time><rating>1< /rating>< Text>
I shop here quite often and spend a great deal of money every year.  Today's visit got me thinking it's time to shop somewhere else.

This year, I spent almost $400 on Christmas ornaments at CB (purchased during the end of October) and last night, I happened to notice all the items I purchased was on sale for 20% off.  So... I decided to stop by to request a price adjustment.

Instead of providing excellent customer service, the manager on duty made it seem as if he was doing me a favor by accommodating my request.  At first, he tried to deter me by telling me I was past the 2 week store policy for price matching but then I had to remind him that I was still within my 90 day refund policy and that I can easily return everything and then repurchase it back at the same price. After thinking this through, he then back peddled and became a bit more willing to assist.  Hmmmm... Not too bright, are we?

For sure I will be expanding my shopping to other comparable retailers like Pottery Barn and William Sonoma going forward.  Bye CB!</Text>

Before I will say what I want to say, I have to offer context and preface it with disclosing that I am very, very, very picky, and therefore not easy to please. I believe that consumers deserve the absolute best (and they seek it) best products, best services. If we do not find what we seek in one business, we take our hard earned dollars elsewhere. Having said that, during my last visit to Costa Mesa's location of Crate & Barrel, I was completely and pleasantly surprised by the attention to detail and wholehearted willingness to please me (and others) that I observed in Arron Weisel. We have been shopping at Crate & Barrel and similar stores since 1992, and this is the single, absolute best shopping experience we have had in 26 years of shopping!!! I am very tough, but i am fair. When complaint is due, I offer it, but when a compliment has been earned, I offer it enthusiastically!!!<//review>

Looking back in my life, I've had many jobs. A college professor, a teleplay writer, a mail clerk, a CNA, a waiter,  a group home owner, and currently, an independent living facility owner. I realized that the best job that I had was being a delivery guy for Pizza Hut when I was 18 in California. I was only working minimum wage, got tips and a free pizza every time I clock out. It was the best job for me because I was genuinely happy with what I was doing. I realize that it doesn't matter what kind of job you have, if you don't love what you do, it's just gonna eat you up inside. Wisdom does come with age.</review>

< review>
This is a great family-owned local filipino restaurant. We stopped by for the first time a couple of weeks ago and split a combo plate and a slice of ube cake.

The combo plate had 2 sliders, 2 chicken skewers, noodles, and 4 lumpias (filipino egg rolls). Plenty of food for the 2 of us.

The ube cake was amazing! Not too sweet, but clear ube flavor and super moist.

Overall I strongly recommend checking this place out.< /review>

<Text>In short, the food is great if you like Filipino food with a twist. I recommend getting the fusion dishes and not the typical Filipino food. The service is very positive (it's a family business).
I went with my parents (both Filipino) for the first time. I ordered the adobo fries, my mom got the adobo bowl, and my dad got the MK combo. I was worried the adobo fries (carne asada fries but with chicken adobo instead) wouldn't work taste-wise but I was wrong. The adobo fries were delicious. My mom said her adobo bowl was okay and my dad said the food was good but not authentic Filipino. For dessert, we got the putoflan, ube cupcake, and a whole fruit pizza. The putoflan was very good, the ube cupcake was good, and the fruit pizza (with a cookie base) was very sweet (I liked it).< /Text>< user_id>
102526432032289515233<//user_id>

< text>
I don‚Äôt normally write reviews but I wanted to share the reason we chose not to purchase our vehicle from this dealership in case it is helpful for management or others.

My husband and I made an appointment to test drive a 2020 Santa Fe. We were working with Joe‚Äôl who was very knowledgeable, helpful and pleasant. The vehicle was priced well and we were ready to purchase. We planned on trading in our car and were passed to another gentleman named Zandro to conduct the valuation for the trade. This encounter is the reason this dealer lost our business.

Zandro initially offered us $500 for our vehicle (2014 Ford Focus SE with 90,000 miles, in good condition). We had priced our car on KBB before we came, so we were well aware that was about $3,000 too low for a trade. Obviously we rejected this offer and let him know the lowest number we would accept. This gentleman proceeded to waste our time, mansplaining how car sales work and insisting we wouldn‚Äôt be able to get more from any other dealer because they would be taking a loss. I work in customer service and a lengthy explanation of your own business practices is almost never relevant to the customer. He was quite rude, uttering phrases like ‚ÄúWhat, you don‚Äôt believe me?‚Äù It quickly became a very unpleasant situation wherein we felt pressured to accept a truly ridiculous offer.

I believe that because the Santa Fe was priced well, they were low-balling us on the trade in to make a higher profit off the transaction. This is poor business practice because the value of our car is not affected by the sale price of a new vehicle and a dealer should not advertise a sale price they can‚Äôt meet. In fairness, he did suggest that we move forward without the trade in. We were unwilling to do that because the Santa Fe was not so well-priced that it made up for the inconvenience of turning a normal single-transaction into multiple. Also, we were put off by the way we were treated. Who wants to do business with someone who has clearly just tried to take advantage of them? This salesman even said at one point ‚ÄúI can throw in a free tank of gas‚Äù as if they don‚Äôt normally do so when you purchase a new car here... Eventually he went upstairs to speak with his manager about a better offer but returned, after some time, with a falsified KBB valuation on our vehicle. At that point we walked out feeling like our time had been wasted by a dishonest car salesman.

Just a couple of days later we made the trip out to Future Hyundai of Concord and our experience was night and day. We were able to interact with management directly at this location. All of the employees we spoke to were polite, transparent and easy to work with. We were offered $3,300 for the vehicle trade no problem. We also got a good price on the Santa Fe, ultimately making out better than we would have at Hanlees. Interestingly, the staff here have had several customers come to them with similar stories regarding Hanlees.

Based on this experience, I would recommend that prospective buyers skip Hanlees and try Future Hyundai instead. I would also suggest that the management at Hanlees evaluate their practices. I‚Äôm not sure how saving a couple grand on a trade-in is more important than making a $30,000+ sale. We don‚Äôt know if this is a management issue or just one bad employee, but it‚Äôs too bad because Joe‚Äôl was excellent and we would have been happy to do business with him.</text>

<Name>Thomas Vrastiak< /Name>< Text>
Where to even begin.  First, WE LOVE OUR HYUNDAI!! Second, run as far away from this dealership as you can!!  My husband and I originally called them because we were refferred via the Costco Auto Program.  The Sonata we wanted was still too expensive, so we asked if they had and demos available.  The salesman Randy said he had a class 2 vehicle available at a substantial discount (a 2015 Hyundai Sonata Limited), and he thought the price was 24-something, but he'd have to look it up. We kept calling back, and he was always busy, but would get back to us.  Finally we got fed up four days later, called the manager Lisa and complained that we had been waiting several days for the price, and that perhaps we should take our business elsewhere....she then said in a very nasty tone that Randy didn't have the price, and was waiting to hear back from Hyundai (this is a lie because Randy was aware of the price and needed to go back through his emails).  Anyway, after she said that perhaps we should take our business elsewhere, she hung up.

We then contacted Hanlee's corporate offices to tell them about the incident, and got email addresses for both the owner (Don Lee) and his second in command (Jim Totah).  Shortly after writing to them both explaining what had transpired we got a call from the second in command Jim Totah.  While we were happy to get a response so quickly Jim made it very clear that we were disturbing him while doing activities with his family....and genuinely seemed annoyed at the bother.  He called again after speaking with Randy (still sounding annoyed) and said Randy should have communicated better???

We still wanted the car, so my husband and I agreed to just get the deal done and we'd never have to deal with them again.  Prior to picking up the car we asked Randy to make sure Android Auto was installed, as older 2015's needed to have a software update to accommodate that feature.  After all the paperwork was done, Randy told me he was going to send an email explaining how to do it because "we knew more about it than he did".

If you've made it this far congratulations....hopefully you'll not make the same mistake we did, and buy your Hyundai anywhere OTHER than Hanlee's!!

***UPDATE***

Its been almost two months since we bought the car, and we were concerned that we had not received our plates.  We called the dealership a few weeks ago and left a message...of course, no return call.
We checked the motor vehicle website, and it said it could take up to six weeks.  Yesterday (almost at two months since purchase) we called motor vehicles to see what was going on....it turns out they only received the paperwork on Nov 17th (shortly after we called the dealership, we can only surmise they forgot)...we bought the car at the beginning of Oct!!

This dealership represents some of the most inept people we've ever seen, and in our estimation they all should lose their jobs....but after talking with Jim Totah we realized that the bad apples go all the way back to the corporate office, so our advice to you is to avoid ALL Hanlee's dealerships!!</Text>

<UserId.>101389389539809868574</UserId.>< Name>
Janet Sanchez< /Name>
<Time>1466641914164< /Time><Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
Okay, so I survived my own kitchen remodel.  The owner Arsen at KHL did an amazing job with our remodel, making great design suggestions that I wouldn't have thought possible. I had a useless big window which faces our side fence.  I wanted to take out the window and cover it with cabinets.  Arsen assured me that it wasn't necessary to take out the window, especially since I live in a gated community.  He covered the window with drywall on the inside, problem solved.  He was very helpful in guiding our choices in the cabinets and hardware; he came up with a solution to a backsplash design where the material I wanted didn't come in a square but in a subway tile.  He also suggested the addition of counter space made possible by moving our fridge about 10 inches. HIs crew of installers/craftsmen are very polite, conscientious and tidy.  Sure, you're going to have dust as this is a construction project, but they make sure to clean up all of their construction debris at the end of the day.  His office manager Jacqui is great in communicating the schedule and troubleshooting when necessary.  All in all, our full kitchen remodel took about 13 days of actual labor. There is a time lag if you get granite installed as they must make a template, then fabricate the counters to fit.  No complaints in that department as  my friends couldn't even get a quote in that amount of time from Lowe's. So if you're considering a kitchen remodel, Arsen will take pride in the work that he and his crew will do for you.</text>
